04228nam a22006135i 9781400832484DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212001nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008324847 a10.1515/97814008324842doi  a(DE-B1597)589792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBD418.3 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a128.22231 aDescombes, Vincent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Mind's Provisions :bA Critique of Cognitivism /cVincent Descombes. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew French Thought Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Introduction: The Complete Holist -- tCHAPTER 1 The Phenomena of Mind -- tCHAPTER 2 Two Sciences? -- tCHAPTER 3 The Anthropological Investigation of the Mind -- tCHAPTER 4 The New Mental Philosophy -- tCHAPTER 5 The Doctrines of Psychical Materialism -- tCHAPTER 6 The Psychology of Computers -- tCHAPTER 7 The Inside and the Out -- tCHAPTER 8 Mechanical Mind -- tCHAPTER 9 Cerebroscopic Exercises -- tCHAPTER 10 The Metaphysics of Mental States -- tCHAPTER 11 The Detachment of the Mind -- tCHAPTER 12 The Historical Conditions of Meaning -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVincent Descombes brings together an astonishingly large body of philosophical and anthropological thought to present a thoroughgoing critique of contemporary cognitivism and to develop a powerful new philosophy of the mind.Beginning with a critical examination of American cognitivism and French structuralism, Descombes launches a more general critique of all philosophies that view the mind in strictly causal terms and suppose that the brain--and not the person--thinks. Providing a broad historical perspective, Descombes draws surprising links between cognitivism and earlier anthropological projects, such as Lévi-Strauss's work on the symbolic status of myths. He identifies as incoherent both the belief that mental states are detached from the world and the idea that states of mind are brain states; these assumptions beg the question of the relation between mind and brain.In place of cognitivism, Descombes offers an anthropologically based theory of mind that emphasizes the mind's collective nature. Drawing on Wittgenstein, he maintains that mental acts are properly attributed to the person, not the brain, and that states of mind, far from being detached from the world, require a historical and cultural context for their very intelligibility.Available in English for the first time, this is the most outstanding work of one of France's finest contemporary philosophers. It provides a much-needed link between the continental and Anglo-American traditions, and its impact will extend beyond philosophy to anthropology, psychology, critical theory, and French studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy of mind. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400832484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400832484.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK